{"cursor":"40762","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"In optics the 'refractive index' or 'index of refraction' n of a substance\n(optical medium) is a dimensionless number that describes how light, or any\nother radiation, propagates through that medium. It is defined as\n: n=\\frac{c}{v} ,\nwhere c is the speed of light in vacuum and v is the speed of light in the\nsubstance. For example, the refractive index of water is 1.33, meaning that\nlight travels 1.33 times as fast in vacuum as it does in water. (See typical\nvalues for different materials here.)\n\nThe historically first occurrence of the refractive index was in Snell's law of\nrefraction, n 1sinθ 1=\nn 2sinθ 2, where θ 1 and\nθ 2 are the angles of incidence of a ray crossing the interface\nbetween two media with refractive indices n 1 and n 2.\n\nBrewster's angle, the critical angle for total internal reflection, and the\nreflectivity of a surface also depend on the refractive index, as described by\nthe Fresnel equations. {{cite book\n  | author = Eugene Hecht title = Optics publisher = Addison-Wesley year = 2002\n  | isbn = 0-321-18878-0}}\n\nThe refractive index can be seen as the factor by which the velocity and the\nwavelength of the radiation are reduced with respect to their vacuum values: The\nspeed of light in a medium is v=c/n and similarly the wavelength in\nthat medium is \\lambda=\\lambda_0/n , where \\lambda_0 is\nthe wavelength of that light in vacuum. This implies that vacuum has a\nrefractive index of 1. Historically other reference media (e.g., air at a\nstandardized pressure and temperature) have been common.\n\nRefractive index of materials varies with the wavelength. This is called\ndispersion; it causes the splitting of white light in prisms and rainbows, and\nchromatic aberration in lenses. In opaque media, the refractive index is a\ncomplex number: while the real part describes refraction, the imaginary part\naccounts for absorption.\n\nThe concept of refractive index is widely used within the full electromagnetic\nspectrum, from x-rays to radio waves. It can also be used with wave phenomena\nother than light (e.g., sound). In this case the speed of sound is used instead\nof that of light and a reference medium other than vacuum must be chosen. {{cite book\n  | author = Lawrence E. Kinsler, Austin R. Frey, Alan B. Coppens, James V.\n  | Sanders title = Fundamentals of Acoustics publisher = John Wiley & Sons,\n  | Inc. year = 2000 isbn = 0-471-84789-5 page = 136}}\n","linknr":697,"url":"Refractive_index","recorded":1362579973,"links":75,"instances":["optics","optics","optics","electromagnetic_radiation","physics","optics","optics","physics","waves","waves","optics","electromagnetism","optics"],"pdf":["http://www.ppl.phys.chiba-u.jp/~makoto/publication/N14-191.pdf","http://www.ppl.phys.chiba-u.jp/~makoto/publication/N14-191.pdf","http://iopscience.iop.org/1464-4258/7/2/003/pdf/1464-4258_7_2_003.pdf","http://iopscience.iop.org/1464-4258/7/2/003/pdf/1464-4258_7_2_003.pdf","http://www.lrsm.upenn.edu/~frenchrh/download/0208fwootenopticalpropertiesofsolids.pdf"],"categories":["Optics","Concepts in physics","Optical mineralogy","Glass physics","Dimensionless numbers","Physical quantities","Article Feedback 5 Additional Articles"],"headings":["Typical values","Microscopic explanation","Dispersion","Complex index of refraction and absorption","Relations to other quantities","Nonscalar, nonlinear, or nonhomogeneous refraction","Refractive index measurement","Applications","See also","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/math/7/b/7/7b78f2dd4ecd813134c0de17086445ee.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5d/RefractionReflextion.svg/650px-RefractionReflextion.svg.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/9/6/e/96e4b8cdfea4d4ba6b779cb05ae374c0.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/3/0/9/309c5ce368df8c65168622e4764f700f.png","//upload.wik